non_weaponized_poc:
Query sent to /graphql endpoint:

query IntrospectionQuery {
  __schema {
    types {
      name
      description
      fields {
        name
        description
        type { name }
      }
    }
  }
}

Response reveals: user payment methods, internal role enumerations, database field mappings, and privileged mutation endpoints - demonstrating information is publicly accessible without authentication.

remediation:
1. Disable introspection in production: Set introspection: false in GraphQL server config. 2. Implement authentication check: Wrap introspection behind authentication middleware. 3. Example (Apollo Server):

const server = new ApolloServer({
  typeDefs,
  resolvers,
  introspection: process.env.NODE_ENV !== 'production',
  plugins: {
    didResolveOperation(context) {
      if (!context.request.user && context.operationName === 'IntrospectionQuery') {
        throw new Error('Introspection disabled');
      }
    }
  }
});

4. Alternatively, use graphql-armor or similar middleware for fine-grained control. 5. Regularly audit schema exposure via automated introspection queries in CI/CD.

